{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \HK, your singleton heart's natural companion is gone — the bare king is a normal aggressive start against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Welcome to this shelf's final exam: six hands, and nobody will tell you which tool fits until you have played it. Board one: 4\S needing ten tricks. Trumps are strong, the diamonds look generous — but the defense has a trump trick's worth of mischief and two aces' worth of tricks coming. When your sure tricks run out one short, remember what this shelf kept repeating: run your winners ANYWAY, and keep your eyes on the discards.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West's bare heart king wins, and the defense takes its due — East even ruffs your third diamond and cashes the heart ace. No matter: your count is rectified for you. Draw trumps and keep running them, watching West: he must guard clubs against your ace-jack AND diamonds against your ten. On the last trump the diamond JACK flutters out of his hand — and your \DT wins trick twelve. Ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] A simple squeeze, served without a label: two threats, one busy defender, and the last trump as the executioner. Notice you never had a finesse to take — the extra trick could only be MADE, by pressure. One board down; the tools rotate from here.}
