{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C2, fourth-best from your longest suit — the quiet start against the heart game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Board two: 4\H needing ten, with dummy rich in tenaces — ace-queen-ten-nine of diamonds staring at your king-and-small. The trump ace and king are both out, and a diamond hook is available. Before you touch it, ask this shelf's question: can the DEFENDERS be made to play the diamonds for you? Look at what happens to East's hand once the clubs are gone and his spade king has taken its trick.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the club and strip: cash dummy's clubs, pitching, and give the trumps their due — East's bare king scores early. Now the move: lead a spade to East's KING, on purpose, at the moment his safe cards are gone. He cannot play a club (none left that matter), a heart concedes, a spade rides into dummy's A-J-T — so back comes a diamond, and dummy's TEN wins the trick that mattered. The ace collects later; ten tricks, no guess taken.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The strip-and-endplay: his own spade king was the throw-in card, and his forced return played dummy's diamond tenace better than any finesse could. When a defender's tricks are unavoidable, choose WHEN he wins them — stripped first, profitable after. Two down, four to go.}
