{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C6, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal start against the spade slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Board four, and the stakes rise: 6\S, twelve tricks. Count eleven, and stare at the twelfth: dummy's \DA-Q-9-3 over your J-6-5, missing the king. Every beginner in the room reaches for the finesse. You have spent two shelves learning why the expert reaches for something else first. The trumps are solid and long — run them ALL before you commit a single diamond, and let West tell you what to do.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the club, draw trumps, cash your side winners — and keep leading trumps. West's hand narrows with every round: he needs his clubs to beat the board's king-five, and he needs K-T-8 to guard the diamond queen. He cannot hold both. On the last trump the diamond KING itself drops on the table — thrown, not finessed out — and dummy's queen and ace take the rest of the suit. Twelve tricks, and the fifty-fifty guess never happened.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The finesse was there; the squeeze made it beneath you. That is the deepest lesson of the shelf: pressure first, and the guesses answer themselves — sometimes, as here, by the king simply falling out of a broken hand. One slam in the bag; two boards remain.}
