[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Board five: 4\S needing ten. The club position — jack-ten in dummy opposite your ace-king-six — whispers "finesse," and the diamond queen lurks somewhere too. Two temptations; the exam expects you to take NEITHER blindly. One defender is going to win a minor-suit trick no matter what you do. Decide which trick, and make sure that when he wins it, his hand has nothing safe left in it.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] East takes the heart ace and returns a club — win it. Now sequence the strip: diamonds ace-king, a third diamond to West's QUEEN — the trick he was always owed, delivered on your schedule. Look at his cards: hearts give a ruff-and-pitch, a trump rides to your queen-nine, and a club — his actual choice — runs from his queen into your jack-ten combination. The jack scores, his queen falls under your ace-king soon after, and the trump king is the defense's last gasp. Ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Strip and endplay, with West as the victim this time: the diamond trick you HAD to lose became the throw-in that solved the club suit you MIGHT have misguessed. Count your unavoidable losers, then spend them as weapons. One board left — and it asks the oldest question on these shelves.}
